Data Collection, Parsing, and Cleaning

Like I mentioned, the data Im using for this tutorial can be found at this link: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_record_progression_100_metres_freestyle.

Taking a quick look at that Wikipedia page, its easy to see there are 4 tables that have data. We are interested in the first, and third tables: the progression of records for Mens and Womens 100m Freestyle over time. The data we are intereseted in is the Time, Name, Nationality, and Date. The other columns are relevant, however for this tutorial we dont need them. There are a few steps that need to be taken to get this data into a form that we can use:

Step 1: Indicate the URL the data is coming from, and storing that in a variable called url.

Step 2: Extract the data for Mens records. We use read_html and html_nodes to find the tables in the document. We access the first table using .[[1]]. html_table then loads that table in, and we set the column names*. Then we use as_data_frame to convert the information loaded into something that we can manipulate and work with!

Step 3: Do the same for the Womens records, except this time we use .[[3]] because it is the third table in the document.

Step 4: Use a mutation to add a gender column onto each of the data frames, were going to use this later on to see differences in Mens and Womens records

Step 5: Finally, we use rbind to combine both the Mens and Womens dataframes into a single dataframe that well call data

*Note: there are 2 placeholder column names, those refer to the blank column and ref column in the data. These wont be used, and will be dropped later.

Code for above steps:

#URL where data is held
url <- "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_record_progression_100_metres_freestyle"

#Extract Men's Data (first table)
mensData <- url %>%
  read_html() %>%
  html_nodes("table") %>%
  .[[1]] %>%
  html_table() %>%
  set_colnames(c("index", "time","placeholder1","swimmer","country","date","meet","location","placeholder2")) %>%
  as_data_frame()

#Extract Women's Data (third table)
womensData <- url %>%
  read_html() %>%
  html_nodes("table") %>%
  .[[3]] %>%
  html_table() %>%
  set_colnames(c("index", "time","placeholder1","swimmer","country","date","meet","location","placeholder2")) %>%
  as_data_frame()


#Add gender column to each data frame
mensData <- mensData %>%
  mutate(gender="Men's")
womensData <- womensData %>%
  mutate(gender="Women's")


#Combine two data frames
data <- rbind(mensData,womensData)

Code to remove the data we dont need, along with a preview of the dataframe

#Drop unnecessary columns
drops <- c("index","placeholder1","placeholder2","meet","location")

Yuck - notice anything wrong with this? The swimmer name is written twice, in two different ways. The date is also written twice, and in a very weird ways. It seems like whoever created this page didnt have us Data people in mind - those pesky Wikipedia Contributors! Not to worry! we clean the data so that we can go about manipulating and analyzing it.

Here are the steps we take to tidy this data:

Step 1: First, convert the time into seconds. Most of it is already like that, but for the ones that are over a minute, there needs to be a modification. We use str_detect to see if there is a : in the time. If there is, that means that we have to take the number after the colon and add 60 to it. We do this by using gsub, and a regex match. If there is no :, we just convert the time to a number using as.numeric.

Step 2: We need to now correct the dates. We use another regex to extract the last part of the date (the Day, Month, and Year). We then use as.Date to take in that remaining value as a real date, that we can sort with.

Step 3: Finally, we use another regex to extract the correct name (First and Last)

Code for above steps, along with a preview of the dataframe:

#Convert time to seconds
data <- data %>%
  mutate(time = ifelse(str_detect(time,':'),
                       as.numeric(gsub('1:','',time))+60,
                       as.numeric(time)))

#Convert date to proper format
data <- data %>%
  mutate(date = gsub('\\d*-\\d*-\\d*-0{4}','',date)) %>%
  mutate(date = as.Date(date, "%d %b %Y"))

#Convert name to proper format
data <- data %>%
  mutate(swimmer = gsub('[^,]*, [A-Z][^A-Z]*','',swimmer))

Exploratory Data Analysis and Visualization

At this point, we have all of the data we need, and have it in a format that will make it easy to manipulate and visualize it. This is the fun part!

Were ready to make our first plot. There are many different functions in the code youre about to see, so here is an explanation of each one:

ggplot(): this is the function that tells R we are plotting something

mapping=aes(y=time, x=date)): the x and y axis are assigned here, x being the date (year) and y being the time of the record

geom_point(): this indicates that we are making a dot plot

ggtitle(): this puts a title at the top of our plot

theme(): this centers the title on the plot

xlab(), ylab(): Assigns labels to the x and y axis

Here is the code, along with the plot thats generated:

#Create a plot that shows record time over the years, grouped by gender
data %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(y=time, x=date)) +
    geom_point() +
    ggtitle("100m Freestyle World Records") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
    xlab("Year") +
    ylab("Time (Seconds)")

Youve made your first plot, congratulations! Notice that there are two separate trends going on - this is due to the gender gap between Men and Women. Remember earlier we added a column for gender to the dataframes? We added that so we could group the two. For this next graph, we are going to separate the two genders into groups. Most of this code is the same as the previous, here are the differences:

geom_line(): Tells R to use make a line graph instead of a normal point plot. This will make it easier to see the progression over the years.

group=gender,color=factor(gender): We add these two arguments to the aes() function. What this tells R is the data should be grouped by gender, and each gender should have its own color.

labs(): We use this to indicate that the legend on the right should have be labeled Gender.

Here is the code for this graph, along with the graph itself:

#Create a plot that shows record time over the years, grouped by gender
data %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(y=time, x=date, group=gender, color=factor(gender))) +
    geom_line() +
    ggtitle("100m Freestyle World Records - Men's vs Women's") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
    xlab("Year") +
    ylab("Time (Seconds)") +
    labs(colour = "Gender")

Note: theres something odd going on with the Mens records; around 1956-1957, there seems to be a slight increase in the record time (there should only be decreases as times go on). Im attributing that to an error in data entry for whoever created the page. Its critical to keep in mind that humans are not perfect, and sometimes the data you get isnt perfect either! Were just going to ignore it, as all of the other records seem to be ok

Something else cool we can do is splitting the data by gender, and then grouping by swimmer. This will allow us to visualize the different swimmers that made records over the years. Most of the code is the same as the previous plots, except for a few changes:

filter(gender==Mens): This takes only the records for the Mens data frame. The same is done for the womens in the second block of code.

group=swimmer, color=factor(swimmer): This time we are grouping by the swimmer, and coloring by swimmer as well

Heres the code for the graphs, and the graphs themselves:

#Create a plot that shows Men's record time over the years, grouped by swimmer
data %>%
  filter(gender=="Men's") %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(y=time, x=date, group=swimmer, color=factor(swimmer))) +
    geom_line() +
    ggtitle("100m Freestyle World Records - Men's") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
    xlab("Year") +
    ylab("Time (Seconds)") +
    labs(colour = "Swimmer")  

#Create a plot that shows Women's record time over the years, grouped by swimmer
data %>%
  filter(gender=="Women's") %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(y=time, x=date, group=swimmer, color=factor(swimmer))) +
    geom_line() +
    ggtitle("100m Freestyle World Records - Women's") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
    xlab("Year") +
    ylab("Time (Seconds)") +
    labs(colour = "Swimmer")

These graphs are interesting, and there some cool inferences we can make from it. Each color represents a different swimmer, and we can see how swimmers beat their own records over a few years. In addition, the blank spaces indicate times where a record wasnt broken - for example, from about 1938-1956, the Womens record wasnt broken by anyone.

Something else we can do is see the number of records were achieved by each swimmer. This goes along with the graph we just made, many times if a swimmer broke a record, they would go on to break their own record for the next few years. To do this, follow these steps:

Step 1 (data preparation): We use filter to get the Mens records.

Step 2: We then use group_by to collect records by each swimmer.

Step 3: Summarize(count=n()) gives us the number of records in each group, which is the number of records for each swimmer.

Step 4 (graphing): This time we use geom_bar, which will this time display a bar plot.

Step 5: The aes() is similar to the previous graphs, but the only change is x=reorder(swimmer,-count),y=count. What this does is tell the graph that swimmer will be on the x axis, and the count (number of records) will be on the y axis. Reorder(swimmer,-count) means that the swimmers will be ordered by their number of records, in descending order.

Step 6: theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) will make the labels on the x axis (swimmers names) be displayed diagonally, otherwise they will overlap and it would be nearly impossible to make the names out.

These same steps are then repeated for the womens records.

Heres the code for the graphs, and the graphs themselves:

#Extract just the Men's records, determine number of records for each swimmer
mensRecordCounts <- data %>%
  filter(gender=="Men's") %>%
  group_by(swimmer) %>%
  summarize(count = n())

#Create a barplot that shows number of records for each swimmer, descending order (Men's)
mensRecordCounts %>%
  ggplot() +
    ggtitle("Total Records by Swimmer (Men's)") +
    geom_bar(aes(x=reorder(swimmer,-count),y=count),stat="identity") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
    xlab("Swimmer") +
    ylab("Records") 

#Extract just the Women's records, determine number of records for each swimmer
womensRecordCounts <- data %>%
  filter(gender=="Women's") %>%
  group_by(swimmer) %>%
  summarize(count = n())

#Create a barplot that shows number of records for each swimmer, descending order (Women's)
womensRecordCounts %>%
  arrange(desc(count)) %>%
  ggplot() +
    ggtitle("Total Records by Swimmer (Women's)") +
    geom_bar(aes(x=reorder(swimmer,-count),y=count),stat="identity") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
    xlab("Swimmer") +
    ylab("Records")

Notice that the two graphs have a very similar distribution, however the top women had about about twice as many records as the men had.

One final thing we can do to visualize this data is see the distribution of records for each country. The code is nearly identical to the code above, however the data is grouped by country instead of swimmer:

The top three countries for Mens records is the United States, Australia, and France. The top three countries for Womens records is Australia, East Germany, and the United States. It seems that the United States and Australia are natural swimmers!

Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning

Now that weve explored and visualized the data a little bit, we can move on to a more complicated concept: linear regression. When we talk about linear regression, what we are trying to do is find a relationship between two variables. In this case, we are going to see if there is a correlation between year and world record time for the Mens 100m Freestyle. In this case, we say that we regress time on year. When we do this, well get two coefficients: One for the Intercept, and one for the Year. This means that assuming the initial year, the time is estimated to be that intercept. Then for each year increase, the time is expected to change by the Year coefficient. The equation for this is Y = B0 + B1(X), where B0 is the intercept, and B1 is the year coefficient, and X is the number of years. This is very similar to a simple graph in math, Y = mx+b (m = slope, b = intercept).

In order to get a better regression, were going to make a modification to the data so that the year 1905 is represented as year 0, and every year after that represents the years since 1905. Below, we extract the date as a numeric value, and subtract 1905 to get the updated year for regression purposes. You can see a visulization of this new data frame in the graph:

#Change the date column to years since 1905
mensRecords <- data %>%
  filter(gender=="Men's") %>%
  mutate(year = as.numeric(format(date,"%Y"))-1905)

#Plot newly upated records, with x axis representing years since 1905
mensRecords %>% ggplot(mapping=aes(y=time, x=year)) +
    geom_line() +
    ggtitle("100m Freestyle World Records - Men's") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
    xlab("Years (Since 1905)") +
    ylab("Time (Seconds)")

When it comes to regression, we start with a null hypothesis. The null hypothesis is what we are going to test against, and decide whether to accept or reject it. In our case, the null hypothesis is that year has NO relationship to the record time. We calculate a linear regression like this:

Step 1: lm(time~year,data=mensRecords) tells R that we are regressing time on the year, using the mensRecords data from above

Step 2: We use the tidy() function to get the coefficients from the calculation, as well as a p.value, which will help us determine whether or not the null hypothesis can be accepted or rejected.

Code for the steps above:

#Null = there is no relationship between year and men's swimming times

#Peform a regression on time vs year
regression_line <- lm(time~year, data=mensRecords)
regression_line %>%
  tidy()
##          term   estimate   std.error statistic      p.value
## 1 (Intercept) 62.7339103 0.342019296  183.4221 5.605320e-70
## 2        year -0.1615565 0.005154519  -31.3427 1.279378e-33

We have 62.7 as our Intercept, and -0.16. What this means that at year 0 (1905), the expected time is 62.73s, and for each year, the time is expected to go down by .16s. In addition, we have a p.value associated with year of 1.28e-33. This is a very low p.value, which shows us that there is a strong correlation; and we can reject our null hypothesis! We can say with statistical confidence that there IS in fact a correlation between year and record time.
